## Phase 0 – First 1–3 Months – Mindset, Setup & Strong Foundation (Must Do First)

### 1. Life-Changing Mindset (Read This Every Single Day)
You are not late — first year is the best time to start AI/ML  
No zero days — even 30 minutes daily is huge progress  
Compare only with your past self — never with Instagram or toppers  
College CGPA matters — aim 7.5+ (below 7.0 hurts many companies)  
Mistakes are your best teachers — make them fast and learn  
Small daily work = compound magic (like ₹100 daily becomes lakhs in years)  
Balance is the real secret: code + college + health + friends + family + rest  
Your future job = 70% self-learning + 20% projects + 10% college marks  
You control your future — not college, not luck, not background  

### 2. Setup Everything (Do in First 7–15 Days)
Laptop Setup  
- Download Python 3.11+ from python.org  
- Install VS Code (free, best editor)  
- Install Git from git-scm.com  
- Chrome browser + extensions: Dark Reader, Grammarly  

Accounts (Make These)  
- GitHub (username simple: yourname-aiml or sanket-ai)  
- LinkedIn (headline: "B.Tech CSE AIML '29 | Learning Python & AI/ML")  
- LeetCode, CodeChef, HackerRank  
- Kaggle.com (very important for datasets & notebooks)  
- Google account for Drive/Colab  

Tools  
- VS Code + Python extension  
- Google Colab (free GPU for ML)  
- Notion or Google Sheet for tracking  

Tracking Template (Simple)  
Every week write:  
- Week number  
- DSA problems solved (easy/medium/hard)  
- Project or coding work done  
- Hours coded/studied  
- One good thing this week  
- One thing to improve  
- Energy level (1–10)  

### 3. Daily Routine Options (Choose One – Stick 80% Days)
Option 1 – Very Busy College Days (45 min–1.5 hours)  
- 20–40 min Python/DSA practice  
- 15–30 min watch short video  
- 10 min revise or push code  

Option 2 – Normal Days (2–3.5 hours)  
- 50–70 min DSA/Python coding  
- 40–60 min project or ML learning  
- 30–45 min video/notes  
- 15–30 min GitHub/LinkedIn  

Option 3 – High Motivation Days (4–6 hours)  
- 1.5 hours DSA  
- 1.5 hours project/ML coding  
- 1 hour theory/video/paper  
- 30 min outreach/application  
- 30 min revision  

Sunday Ritual (1–2 hours)  
- Review week (see tracking)  
- Re-solve 5–10 hard problems  
- Update GitHub  
- Plan next week  
- Relax — watch movie or meet friends  

### 4. Health & Balance – Never Skip This
- Sleep 7–8 hours every night — brain needs it to learn  
- Walk, play, gym or exercise 20–45 min daily  
- Drink 2–3 liters water  
- One light day per week (revision + chill only)  
- Eat normal home food — reduce junk  
- Talk to family/friends — don’t become coding robot  
- If stressed/tired — take break, sleep extra, watch funny video  

Phase 1 – Absolute Beginner to Early Intermediate (Months 1–9 First Year)

1. Master Python (The Heart of AI/ML)  
Step-by-Step Learning Order (Do in Sequence)  
1. Install Python + VS Code (1–2 days)  
2. Hello World, print, input, comments, variables  
3. Data types: int, float, str, bool, None  
4. Operators: + - * / % // ** == != > < and or not  
5. Conditionals: if, else, elif, nested if  
6. Loops: for range, while, break, continue, pass  
7. Lists: create, append/pop/remove, index, slice, loop  
8. Tuples: create, unpack, immutable  
9. Dictionaries: key-value, get, items/keys/values, update  
10. Sets: add/remove, union/intersection/difference  
11. Functions: def, return, default args, *args, **kwargs  
12. Strings: upper/lower, split/join, strip, replace, find  
13. File handling: open/read/write/close txt/csv files  
14. Basic OOP: class, object, __init__, self, methods  
15. Modules: import math, random, datetime, os, sys  
16. Exception handling: try-except-else-finally, raise  
17. List/dict/set comprehension  
18. Lambda functions, map/filter/reduce  
19. Generators (yield basics)  
20. Decorators intro (simple)  

Resources (Free & Super Beginner Friendly)  
- CodeWithHarry Python full course (Hindi – clearest for Indians)  
- Apna College Python playlist (Hindi/English mix)  
- freeCodeCamp Python for Beginners (English, 4 hours)  
- Automate the Boring Stuff with Python (free book online)  
- W3Schools Python (quick reference + examples)  

Goal after 4–6 months  
- Write 100+ small programs without looking at video  
- Solve problems like calculator, guessing game, pattern print, student manager, file organizer  

2. Easy DSA in Python (Build Logic)  
Platforms (Free & Easy)  
- CodeChef Starters contests (best for beginners)  
- LeetCode easy section  
- GeeksforGeeks beginner practice  
- HackerRank Python domain  

First 9 Months Topics (Only Easy to Medium)  
Months 1–3 (Easy)  
- Pattern printing (stars, numbers, alphabet, diamond)  
- Basic math (prime check, factorial, GCD, sum of digits, reverse number)  
- Arrays/lists (sum, max/min, second max, reverse, rotate left/right)  
- Strings (palindrome, count vowels/consonants, reverse words, anagram)  
- Simple recursion (factorial, fibonacci, sum of digits)  

Months 4–6 (Easy-Medium)  
- Searching: linear, binary search basics  
- Sorting: bubble, selection, insertion intro  
- Two pointers easy  
- Hashing basics (dict usage)  

Months 7–9 (Medium Intro)  
- Sliding window simple  
- Linked list basics (reverse, cycle detection)  
- Stack/queue simple problems  

Target: 300–600 problems  
- 200–400 easy  
- 100–200 medium  
Do 5–10 problems per week — think first, don’t copy  

3. First Python Projects (Build Confidence)  
Do 8–12 small projects in first year.

Project Ideas (Easy to Medium)  
1. Number Guessing Game (easy)  
2. To-Do List Manager (add/delete/show/save to file)  
3. Quiz Game (10–20 MCQ, score, timer)  
4. Student Marks System (add, show, average, topper)  
5. Simple Calculator (menu based)  
6. Password Generator (strong random passwords)  
7. Rock Paper Scissors (play with computer)  
8. Currency Converter (hardcode rates)  
9. File Organizer (sort files by type)  
10. Weather Checker (use free API)  
11. Expense Tracker (add expense, show monthly)  
12. Simple Chatbot (rule-based)  

Rule  
- Finish one project every 3–5 weeks  
- Put every project on GitHub  
- Make simple README: name, what it does, how to run, screenshots  
- Bonus: deploy easy ones with Streamlit later  

4. Start AI/ML Basics (No Heavy Math Yet)  
Goal: Understand concepts — no deep coding yet.

What to Learn (Very Easy)  
- What is AI? (machines doing smart things)  
- What is Machine Learning? (learn from data)  
- Types: supervised (with answers), unsupervised (no answers), reinforcement  
- What is data? (numbers, text, images, videos)  
- Simple libraries: numpy (fast math), pandas (data tables)  

Resources  
- Apna College AI/ML intro playlist (Hindi – super simple)  
- CodeWithHarry Machine Learning intro (Hindi)  
- 3Blue1Brown Neural Network videos (English, beautiful)  
- Kaggle Intro to Machine Learning course (free, 4 hours)  

Goal  
- Understand: ML = computer finds patterns in data  
- Know difference: AI > ML > Deep Learning  

